etymology_text: The singular instructive case of kuka. Originally a lesser used variant of kuin; modern differences between the two were introduced when the language was standardized.

examples.text: Sain viestisi, kun olin jo matkalla lentokentälle.
examples.english: I got your message when I was already on my way to the airport.

examples.text: Hän ilmestyi antamaan ohjeita, kun olin jo saanut työn valmiiksi.
examples.english: He showed up to give instructions when I had already finished the job.

glosses: when, as, while (temporal: at the same time or instant that)

examples.text: Tulen tapaamaan sinua, kun(han) saan tämän valmiiksi.
examples.english: I will come to see you as soon as I finish this job.

glosses: as soon as, once; expresses that the event of the main clause takes place immediately after that of the subclause, often used with the clitic -han

examples.text: Hän menetti työpaikkansa, kun tuli aina myöhässä.
examples.english: She lost her job because she was always late.

examples.text: En voi tulla huomenna, minulla kun on aamuvuoro.
examples.english: I cannot come tomorrow as I have the morning shift.

etymology_text: The singular instructive case of kuka. Originally a lesser used variant of kuin; modern differences between the two were introduced when the language was standardized.

examples.text: There's a certain man here who'd like to see the leader.
examples.ref: Täällä on eräs mies, kun haluaisi tavata johtajaa. [standard: Täällä on eräs mies, joka haluaisi tavata johtajaa.]

examples.text: Who is that who is shouting?
examples.ref: Kuka se on, kun huutaa? [standard: Kuka se on, ken huutaa?]

etymology_text: Internationalism (see English pseudo-), ultimately from Ancient Greek ψευδής (pseudḗs).

From Proto-Finnic *koira, from earlier *koj(e)ra, from Proto-Uralic *kojera (“male animal”) (whence also koiras (“male animal”)), derived from Proto-Uralic *koje (“male, man”), in which case the word probably originally meant "male dog" specifically (and possibly displaced peni in the general sense of "dog").

derived.english: it's the dog that gets hit that yelps; refers to the belief that the person protesting loudest is likely to be guilty; used similarly to English a hit dog will holler, the lady doth protest too much
